snippet.textDisplay: Used to like apple products years ago, first one i had was a g3, spent 1000 gbp roughly on a brand new g5, which was a big spend back then. The software was expensive for what I wanted to do, but I persisted, as apple had a rep back then for being solid machines, or so I thought. Literally the week the years warranty ran out the lcd screen decided to leak, and it killed the computer. There was an apple store in my city at the time, very posh it was, so I thought if i go see them, maybe they can offer help or a suggestion for getting me back up and running. No such luck, I basically got told to piss off by a miserable assistant. I had backed up my work for the year, but any work in progress was lost. I was so angry at apple for not offering any help, I was just under 1000 pounds out of pocket with a giant white dead thing sitting on my desk. It took me 6 months to finally throw the piece of shit out and I have never bought anything by that shitty company ever again. In a way im glad, because back then apple were on motorola chips and not intel, and I found the pc to be far more liberating. Im still pissed at them for taking my money and giving me a shit product in return which lasted a year, yes, still pissed, because i worked for that money, they didnt, they just gave me a sub standard piece of plastic shit and then told me to go fuck myself when it broke. Ill never buy an apple product again.

snippet.textDisplay: The processor is not the Xeon W-3275, it is the Xeon W-3275M. The difference is that the M-variant supports 2TB compared to 1TB on the Xeon W-3275. This is why Apple made the 1.5TB RAM only available for the 24- and 28-core, since both of them support 2TB of RAM in total. However, if you never wanted more than 1TB of RAM then it is just a useless expensive feature.

snippet.textDisplay: There's no doubt these things are a work of art and fantastic quality but the pricing on these is hideous. I also echo what people say about Dell's support. It is extremely good. Sometimes a little painful at the initial contact with a person on the phone but once the engineer is booked it's all totally painless. I have a Dell PC with 2 X eight core Xeons and 128 gig of RAM which I use in my Music recording studio. It has the option of a Thunderbolt 2 card and I needed to test if the Presonus Quantum would work so Dell sent me one to test on a sale or return basis. It worked fine so I bought it. The equivalent MAC would cost me about £8,000 and this PC is amazing, very quiet and totally reliable and trouble free. I am essentially a PC user but I do like Apple products (I have iPhone 11, various iPads etc), but they are just so incredibly over-priced, and their memory upgrade prices are ridiculous!
